rraine’ (see   Lorraine  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Lorne","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from the district of Lorn (Argyll).","English: perhaps a shortened form of   Loring  , a surname which is well evidenced in medieval southwestern England, where <i>Lorne</i> is later recorded."]},{"name":"Lorraine","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Emile, Perrine, Pierre.","French and English: habitational name from Lorraine, a region in the northeastern part of France. Its name derives from the name of the medieval kingdom of Lotharingia, which in turn was named for its sovereign <i>Lothar</i> (a personal name composed of the elements <i>hlūd</i> ‘famous, renowned’ + <i>hari</i>, <i>heri</i> ‘army’).","Altered form of French   Lorrain  , a variant of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":26,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Margaret Loring was born in 1356, in Chalgrave, Bedfordshire, England, her father, Nigel Loring, was 36 and her mother, Margaret Beaupel, was 33. She married Lord Thomas Peyvre 4th Baron Peyvre in 1368, in Chalgrave, Bedfordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1449, in Toddington, Bedfordshire, England, at the age of 93."},"et":{"1356–1449":"1356–1449","1352–1429":"1352–1429","1354–Male":"1354–Surnud","1382–1409":"1382–1409","1320–1386":"1320–1386","1323–1386":"1323–1386","1352":"1352","22 September 1429":"22. september 1429","1382":"1382","1368":"1368","1356":"1356","1323":"1323","1377":"1377","1354":"1354","1386":"1386","1320":"1320","March 1386":"märts 1386","18 March 1386":"18. märts 1386","1409":"1409","26 July 1409":"26. juuli 1409","1429":"1429","1449":"1449",", , Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Toddington, Bedfordshire, England":"Toddington, Bedfordshire, England","England":"England","Chalgrave, Bedfordshire, England":"Chalgrave, Bedfordshire, England","Castle Cary, Somerset, England":"Castle Cary, Somerset, England"},"fi":{"1356–1449":"1356–1449","1352–1429":"1352–1429","1354–Male":"1354–Kuollut","1382–1409":"1382–1409","1320–1386":"1320–1386","1323–1386":"1323–1386","1352":"1352","22 September 1429":"22. syyskuuta 1429","1382":"1382","1368":"1368","1356":"1356","1323":"1323"